Environmentally friendly. Humans are using up earth\u2019s valuable resources faster than it has time to catch up with. By wearing vintage, you\u2019re helping to stop the current high demand. It also prevents the mistreatment of animals & people. Animals are hunted to the point many have gone extinct in the name of fashion. Humans are used as slaves in sweat shops, exploited by their fellow man. Save our earth- buy vintage!\n2. Offers more unique styles. Clothing wasn\u2019t mass produced to the extent it is today, so there was opportunity for designers to make their own lines of clothing, resyulting in many styles! Much clothing was handmade for that personal flair. There wasn\u2019t much cookie-cutter fashion like today.\n3. Flattering for your figure. Designers took time to tailor garments to the specific curves of the body, which means a flattering silhouette for all.\n4. Often better quality. Mass production=less quality. Garments were made with more care because people had appreciation for the importance of being well-dressed.\n5. Less expensive. Clothing today wears out very fast, so it needs to be replaced often. But garments from 50 years ago are still going strong.\n6. Supports small businesses. We have a story all our own. My hope is I will be able to have a little more income for my medical bills because I have expensive health issues. Buying from modern name brands pours money into the mouths of millionaires behind the tag. When you buy from us, you\u2019re helping a real person who\u2019s just trying to get by & provide for their family.\n7. Encourages creativity. And self expression! Will you mix it with other eras? These pieces have personally seen the world change from decade to decade.\n9. Leads to a special connection with people. You\u2019ll feel good about buying vintage. may contain: 1 person, sitting"}},{"node":{"comments_disabled":false,"__typename":"GraphSidecar","id":"2040409845111555618","edge_media_to_caption":{"edges":[{"node":{"text":"Zorba the Greek (1964)\n\nOPA! Zorba the Greek is an interesting (borderline strange) little movie made great by a pair of iconic performances.\n\nIn a nutshell: Upon inheriting a mine, English author Basil (Alan Bates) relocates to Crete where he runs in with the fun-loving, zest-for-life Zorba (Anthony Quinn). Adventures ensue.\n\nIcon #1: Anthony Quinn as Zorba the Greek. Quinn embodies Zorba's raw, joyous passion for life with every boisterous word, gesture, and dance. Watching Zorba woo the lonely Madame Hortense, or build a lignite mine, or liquoring up monks, or simply dancing on the beach is a riveting flood of energy with Quinn in command. A career defining performance.\n\nIcon #2: Lila Kedrova as the French war widow Madame Hortense. Kedrova stuns. To call her performance a revelation would be a start; to call her a tour-de-force would be not saying enough. She is heartbreaking and tragic and gentle and vulnerable and glamorous and pitiful. Kedrova more than matches Quinn's charisma and energy - she arguably bests him in his own movie. She won an extremely well deserved Best Supporting Actress Oscar for her work (an all-time best in the category)\n\nZorba the Greek is tremendous fun for most of its runtime, and then BAM shit gets dark and heavy. That's where the movie's brilliance lies, actually. We can't appreciate the light without knowing darkness and, by God, Zorba the Greek does not shy away from thrusting us into the dark (a woman is murdered by a mob, locals wait like vultures for an ill woman to die so they may steal her belongings)\n\nDespite the powerful, bleak commentary on poverty, misogyny, and the dark side of humanity, Zorba the Greek, ultimately succeeds in being a raucous celebration of life. You'll be confused how to feel some moments of Zorba the Greek, but with Quinn et al in charge, you'll be happy you're feeling at all.\n\n8.4/10\n\nHave you seen Zorba the Greek? Let's hear it!\n\n#zorbathegreek #anthonyquinn #alanbates #lilakedrova #movies #film #cinema #hollywood #oldhollywood #classicfilms #greatestfilms #oscars #academyawards #afi #bfi #turnerclassicmovies outdoor"}},{"node":{"comments_disabled":false,"__typename":"GraphImage","id":"2040409792446625645","edge_media_to_caption":{"edges":[{"node":{"text":"Leslie Howard and Norma Shearer in Romeo and Juliet, 1936. One reason censorship was enforced in Hollywood starting in 1933 was  Norma Shearer. The Catholic Legion of Decency had expressed especial outrage over Shearer's early Thirties pictures The Divorcee, A Free Soul and Strangers When We Meet. The Legion called her the personification of Sin and forbade Catholics to attend her films. Immediately after the imposition of the Hayes Code, Shearer's husband Irving Thalberg, who was head of production at MGM, set about salvaging her image and her box office potential. From then on she only played grand historical or motherly figures. Nothing offensive. The result were films like Romeo and Juliet and The Barretts of Wimpole Street. They're not bad, but they lack the spark that was so invigorating in the performances from early part of Shearer's career. #oldhollywood #classichollywood #vintagehollywood #moviestars #lesliehoward #normashearer #romeoandjuliet #classicfilm #classicmovies #classicfilmstars #classicmoviestars #oldmoviestars @goodoldmovies\nMade by @Image.Downloader\n\u00b7 \u00b7 \u00b7\nThis is so Friday! A true tour de force, Rita Hayworth in \u201cTonight And Every Night\u201d, 1945 \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014 Rita Hayworth\u2019s background was almost exclusively in dance. Born Margarita Carmen Cansino into a well-known Spanish dancing family (her father was Spanish Gypsy flamenco dancer Eduardo Cansino, and her mother was an American former Ziegfeld girl of Irish and English descent), she began dancing under the tutelage of her father when she was 4 years old. Eduardo soon realized that his daughter had an exceptional talent, and he eventually took her south from their home in Chula Vista, CA to the Mexican city of Tijuana where they performed as a dancing duo. Shy, quiet and self-conscious offstage, Margarita came alive when she danced and audience members often noticed the dichotomy between the fiery creature dancing onstage and the silent girl they witnessed offstage. The experience dancing with her father in Tijuana certainly honed Margarita\u2019s dancing abilities, and it was there that she learned the ins and outs of show business, something that would help her when she soon went to Hollywood. \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014 #oldhollywood #vintage Di rumah tersebut, dulu dia mengalami kekerasan fisik dan seksual oleh ayahnya sendiri. Dan teman-temannya yang tergabung dalam The Losers' Club menjadi penghiburnya.Saat berkeliling, Beverly juga menemukan kartu berisi puisi buatan Ben. Trailer itu turut menampilkan adegan saat Beverly muda (Sophia Lillis) terpesona akan puisi tersebut.Di saat itulah, rumah tersebut berisi hal yang aneh. Sejumlah lalat beterbangan, percakapan Mrs Kersh yang ganjil, hingga sejumlah luka Mrs Kersh yang membuat Beverly merasa ingin cepat pergi.\u00a0Keinginan perginya semakin tinggi kala Beverly menemukan hal yang membuatnya heran.
